        />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>
              The atomic bomb dropped on Nagasaki, known as ‚ÄúFat Man‚Äù, was more
              powerful than ‚ÄúLittle Boy‚Äù used on Hiroshima, but it caused less
              destruction because the city‚Äôs terrain reduced the impact of the
              blast. Source: Nevada Department of Veterans Services
            </i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The legacy:</strong> August 6 marks 80 years since the US
            dropped the ‚ÄúLittle Boy‚Äù atomic bomb on Hiroshima, followed three
            days later by the Nagasaki attack (<a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-8-aug-25-foundations-h1-15-see-photos"
              target="_blank"
              >see photos</a
            >). While about 70,000 died instantly in Hiroshima, total deaths
            reached around 140,000 by the end of 1945, with survivors enduring
            decades of illness from radiation exposure. In Nagasaki, the
            estimated death toll was 40,000 to 70,000 (<a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-8-aug-25-foundations-h1-16-number-estimates"
              target="_blank"
              >number estimates</a
            >).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The lesson:</strong> These remain the sole wartime uses of
            nuclear weapons, yet their shadow still shapes global policy and
            attitudes toward nuclear warfare. Survivors and peace groups urge
            nuclear abolition, warning that these weapons bring nothing but
            destruction and suffering. Their message is increasingly pressing
            amid signs of renewed nuclear arms races, undermining decades of
            disarmament efforts.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The future:</strong> The Hiroshima bomb had a yield of 15
            kilotons, which would be considered low by modern standards.
            Currently, the largest US nuclear weapon is 80 times more powerful,
            and experts warn that a single modern detonation over a major city
            could kill vast numbers instantly. There are
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-8-aug-25-foundations-h1-17-more-than-12-000-nuclear-weapons"
              target="_blank"
              >more than 12,000 nuclear weapons</a
            >
            in the hands of nine countries (the US, Russia, China, France, the
            UK, India, Pakistan, North Korea, and Israel). The US and Russia
            hold about 90% of the global stockpile, but smaller powers are also
            expanding their capabilities.
          </p>
